#defining a function to assign correct column name 
def rename_columns(df):
    df.columns = [
        "Indicator",
        "Number of Persons - Both",
        "Percentage - Both",
        "Number of Persons - Male",
        "Percentage - Male",
        "Number of Persons - Female",
        "Percentage - Female"
    ]
    return df

In [23]:
# Clean and convert these columns to numeric
for col in numeric_columns:
    combined_df[col] = (
        combined_df[col]
        .astype(str)                      # Ensure column is string
        .str.replace(",", "")             # Remove commas
        .str.extract(r'(\d+\.?\d*)')      # Extract numeric part
        .astype(float)                    # Convert to float
    )
In [25]:
# Drop rows where all these numeric columns are NaN
combined_df = combined_df.dropna(subset=numeric_columns, how='all')

In [35]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Group by province and calculate the sum of "Number of Persons - Both"
province_summary = combined_df.groupby("Province")["Number of Persons - Both"].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)

# Reset index to make it easier to plot
province_summary = province_summary.reset_index()

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x="Province", y="Number of Persons - Both", data=province_summary, palette="viridis")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.title("Total Number of Persons (Both Genders) by Province")
plt.xlabel("Province")
plt.ylabel("Number of Persons")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
